<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,151,860]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,728,752]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is closely resembles to 
<taxonomicName box="[729,791,729,752]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Maiestas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crura">
<emphasis box="[729,791,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">crura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the subgenital plate has a more rounded lateral margin and apex (
<figureCitation box="[309,390,764,788]" captionStart="FIGURE 21. M" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1587,1610]" captionTargetBox="[222,1353,197,1531]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[188,1398,165,1566]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 21. M. remigia sp. nov. A: male pygofer lobe, lateral view; B: valve, ventral view; C: subgenital plate, ventral view; D: style, dorsal view; E &amp; F: aedeagus and connective, dorsal and lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206136/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number box="[362,390,764,788]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
C) and the style apophysis is smooth (
<figureCitation box="[815,897,764,788]" captionStart="FIGURE 21. M" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1587,1610]" captionTargetBox="[222,1353,197,1531]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[188,1398,165,1566]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 21. M. remigia sp. nov. A: male pygofer lobe, lateral view; B: valve, ventral view; C: subgenital plate, ventral view; D: style, dorsal view; E &amp; F: aedeagus and connective, dorsal and lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206136/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number box="[868,897,764,788]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,151,860]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,332,800,824]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of this species is based on the oar-like shape of the connective and aedeagus in lateral view.
</paragraph>
